# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: opensuse
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] A **Linux distribution**, often abbreviated as **distro**, is an operating system that includes the Linux kernel for its kernel functionality.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Although the name does not imply product distribution per se, a distro—if distributed on its own—is often obtained via a website intended specifically for the purpose.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Distros have been designed for a wide variety of systems ranging from personal computers (for example, Linux Mint and Zorin OS) to servers (for example, Red Hat Enterprise Linux) and from embedded devices (for example, OpenWrt) to supercomputers (for example, Rocks Cluster Distribution).
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] A distro typically includes many components in addition to the Linux kernel.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Commonly, it includes a package manager, an init system (such as systemd, OpenRC, SysVinit, or runit), GNU tools and libraries, documentation, IP network configuration utilities, the getty TTY setup program, and many more.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Typically, most of the included software is free and open-source software – made available both as binary for convenience and as source code to allow for modifying it.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] A distro may also include proprietary software that is not available in source code form, such as a device driver binary.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] A distro may be described as a particular assortment of application and utility software (various GNU tools and libraries, for example), packaged with the Linux kernel in such a way that its capabilities meet users' needs.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The software is usually adapted to the distribution and then combined into software packages by the distribution's maintainers.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The software packages are available online in repositories, which are storage locations usually distributed around the world.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Beside "glue" components, such as the distribution installers (for example, Debian-Installer and Anaconda) and the package management systems, very few packages are actually written by a distribution's maintainers.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Distributions have been designed for a wide range of computing environments, including desktops, servers, laptops, netbooks, mobile devices (phones and tablets), and embedded systems.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] There are commercially backed distributions, such as Red Hat Enterprise Linux (Red Hat), openSUSE (SUSE) and Ubuntu (Canonical), and entirely community-driven distributions, such as Debian, Slackware, Gentoo and Arch Linux.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Most distributions come ready-to-use and prebuilt for a specific instruction set, while some (such as Gentoo) are distributed mostly in source code form and must be built before installation.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Linus Torvalds developed the Linux kernel and distributed its first version, 0.01, in 1991.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Linux was initially distributed as source code only, and later as a pair of downloadable floppy disk images: one bootable and containing the Linux kernel itself, and the other with a set of GNU utilities and tools for setting up a file system.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Since the installation procedure was complicated, especially in the face of growing amounts of available software, distributions sprang up to simplify it.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The two oldest, still active distribution projects started in 1993.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The SLS distribution was not well maintained, so in July 1993 a new SLS-based distribution, Slackware, was released by Patrick Volkerding.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Also dissatisfied with SLS, Ian Murdock set to create a free distribution by founding Debian in August 1993, with first public BETA released in January 1994 and first stable version in June 1996.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Users were attracted to Linux distributions as alternatives to MS-DOS compatible operating systems, Windows, Classic Mac OS, and proprietary versions of Unix.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Most early adopters were familiar with Unix from work or school.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] They embraced Linux distributions for their low (or absent) cost, and the availability of the source code for most or all of their software.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] As of 2025, Linux has become more popular in server and embedded devices markets than in the desktop market.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] It is used in approximately 64.5% of web servers; its current operating system market share is about 2.51%, and its desktop operating system market share is about 2.94%.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide an installation system akin to that provided with other modern operating systems.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Other distributions, including Gentoo Linux, provide only the binaries of a basic kernel, compilation tools, and an installer; the installer compiles all the requested software for the specific architecture of the user's computer, using these tools and the software's source code.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Distributions are normally segmented into *packages*.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Each package contains a specific application or service.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Examples of packages are a library for handling the PNG image format, a collection of fonts, and a web browser.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The package is typically provided as compiled code, with installation and removal of packages handled by a package management system (PMS) rather than a simple file archiver.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Each package intended for such a PMS contains meta-information such as its description, version number, and its dependencies (other packages it requires to run).
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The package management system evaluates this meta-information to allow package searches, perform automatic upgrades to newer versions, and to check that all dependencies of a package are present (and either notify the user to install them, or install them automatically).
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The package can also be provided as source code to be compiled on the system.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Most distributions install packages, including the kernel and other core operating system components, in a predetermined configuration.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] A few now require or permit configuration adjustments at first install time.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] This makes installation less daunting, particularly for new users, but is not always acceptable.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] For specific requirements, much software must be carefully configured to be useful, to work correctly with other software, or to be secure, and local administrators are often obliged to spend time reviewing and reconfiguring it.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Some (but not all) distributions go to considerable lengths to adjust and customize the software they include, and some provide configuration tools to help users do so.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] By obtaining and installing *everything* normally provided in a distribution, an administrator may create a "distribution less" installation.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] It is possible to build such systems from scratch, avoiding distributions altogether.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] One needs a way to generate the first binaries until the system is *self-hosting*.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] This can be done via compilation on another system capable of building binaries for the intended target (possibly by cross-compilation).
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions is due to technical, organizational, and philosophical variation among vendors and users.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The permissive licensing of free software means that users with sufficient knowledge and interest can customize any extant distribution, or design one to suit their own needs.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Rolling Linux distributions are kept current using small and frequent updates.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The terms *partially rolling* and *partly rolling* (along with synonyms *semi-rolling* and *half-rolling*), *fully rolling*, *truly rolling* and *optionally rolling* are sometimes used by software developers and users.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Repositories of **rolling distributions** usually contain very recent software releases—often the latest stable versions available.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] They have pseudo-releases and installation media that are simply snapshots of the distribution at the time of the installation image's release.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Typically, a rolling-release OS installed from older installation medium can be fully updated after it is installed.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Depending on the usage case, there can be pros and cons to both standard release and rolling release software development methodologies.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] In terms of the software development process, **standard releases** require significant development effort to keep old versions up-to-date by propagating bug fixes back to the newest branch, versus focusing on the newest development branch.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Also, unlike rolling releases, standard releases require more than one code branch to be developed and maintained, which increases the workload of the software developers and maintainers.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] On the other hand, software features and technology planning are easier in standard releases due to a better understanding of upcoming features in the next version(s).
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Software release cycles can also be synchronized with those of major upstream software projects, such as desktop environments.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] As for the user experience, standard releases are often viewed as more stable and bug-free since software conflicts can be more easily addressed and the software stack more thoroughly tested and evaluated, during the software development cycle.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] For this reason, they tend to be the preferred choice in enterprise environments and mission-critical tasks.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] However, rolling releases offer more current software which can also provide increased stability and fewer software bugs along with the additional benefits of new features, greater functionality, faster running speeds, and improved system and application security.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Regarding software security, the rolling release model can have advantages in timely security updates, fixing system or application security bugs and vulnerabilities, that standard releases may have to wait till the next release for or patch in various versions.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] In a rolling release distribution, where the user has chosen to run it as a highly dynamic system, the constant flux of software packages can introduce new unintended vulnerabilities.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] A "live" distribution is a Linux distribution that can be booted from removable storage media such as optical discs or USB flash drives, instead of being installed on and booted from a hard disk drive.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The portability of installation-free distributions makes them advantageous for applications such as demonstrations, borrowing someone else's computer, rescue operations, or as installation media for a standard distribution.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] When the operating system is booted from a read-only medium such as a CD or DVD, any user data that needs to be retained between sessions cannot be stored on the boot device but must be written to another storage device, such as a USB flash drive or a hard disk drive.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide a "live" form in addition to their conventional form, which is a network-based or removable-media image intended to be used only for installation; such distributions include antiX, SUSE, Ubuntu, Linux Mint, MX Linux and Fedora Linux.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Some distributions, including Knoppix, Puppy Linux, Devil-Linux, SuperGamer, SliTaz GNU/Linux and dyne:bolic, are designed primarily for live use.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Additionally, some minimal distributions can be run directly from as little space as one floppy disk without the need to change the contents of the system's hard disk drive.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The website DistroWatch lists many Linux distributions and displays some of the ones that have the most web traffic on the site.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The Wikimedia Foundation released an analysis of the browser User Agents of visitors to WMF websites until 2015, which includes details of the most popular Operating System identifiers, including some Linux distributions.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Many of the popular distributions are listed below.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Whether such operating systems count as a "Linux distribution" is a controversial topic.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] They use the Linux kernel, so the Linux Foundation and Chris DiBona, Google's former open-source chief, agree that Android is a Linux distribution; others, such as Google engineer Patrick Brady, disagree by noting the lack of support for many GNU tools in Android, including glibc.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Other Linux-kernel-based operating systems include Tizen, Mer/Sailfish OS, KaiOS and Amazon's Kindle firmware.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Lightweight Linux distributions are those that have been designed with support for older hardware in mind, allowing older hardware to still be used productively, or, for maximum possible speed in newer hardware by leaving more resources available for use by applications.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Examples include antiX, Damn Small Linux (based on antiX), Tiny Core Linux, Puppy Linux and Slitaz.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The Free Standards Group was an organization formed by major software and hardware vendors that aims to improve interoperability between different distributions.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Among their proposed standards are the Linux Standard Base, which defines a common ABI and packaging system for Linux, and the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard which recommends a standard file naming chart, notably the basic directory names found on the root of the tree of any Linux filesystem.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Those standards, however, see limited use, even among the distributions developed by members of the organization.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions means that not all software runs on all distributions, depending on what libraries and other system attributes are required.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Packaged software and software repositories are usually specific to a particular distribution, though cross-installation is sometimes possible on closely related distributions.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] One of solutions for interdistribution issues, particularly to run software created for a distribution on another, is by using container such as Distrobox.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] There are several ways to install a Linux distribution.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The most popular method of installing Linux is by booting from a live USB memory stick, which can be created by using a USB image writer application and the ISO image, which can be downloaded from various Linux distribution websites.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] DVD disks, CD disks, network installations and even other hard drives can also be used as "installation media".
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] In the 1990s, Linux distributions were installed using sets of floppy disks, but this has been abandoned by all major distributions.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] By the 2000s, many distributions offered CD and DVD sets with the vital packages on the first disk and less important packages on later ones.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Some distributions, such as Debian also enabled installing over a network after booting from either a set of floppy disks or a CD with only a small amount of data on it.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] New users tend to begin by partitioning a hard drive to keep their formerly installed operating system.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The Linux distribution can then be installed on its own separate partition without affecting formerly saved data.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] In a Live CD setup, the computer boots the entire operating system from CD without first installing it on the computer's hard disk.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Many distributions have a Live CD *installer*, where the computer boots the operating system from the disk, and it can then be installed on the computer's hard disk, providing a seamless transition from the OS running from the CD to the OS running from the hard disk.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Both servers and personal computers that come with Linux already installed are available from vendors including Hewlett-Packard, Dell and System76.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] On embedded devices, Linux is typically held in the device's firmware and may or may not be consumer-accessible.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Anaconda, one of the more popular installers, is used by Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Fedora (which uses the Fedora Media Writer) and other distributions to simplify the installation process.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Debian, Ubuntu and many others use Debian-Installer.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The process of constantly switching between distributions is often referred to as "distro hopping".
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Virtual machine software such as VirtualBox and VMware Workstation virtualize hardware allowing users to test live media on a virtual machine without installing to the real system.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Some websites like DistroWatch offer lists of distributions, and link to screenshots of operating systems as a way to get a first impression of various distributions.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Some distributions let the user install Linux on top of their current system, such as coLinux.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Linux is installed to the Windows hard disk partition, and can be started from inside Windows itself.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Virtual machines (such as VirtualBox or VMware Workstation) also make it possible for Linux to be run inside another OS.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The VM software simulates a separate computer onto which the Linux system is installed.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] After installation, the virtual machine can be booted as if it were an independent computer.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Some specific proprietary software products are not available in any form for Linux.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] As of September 2015, the Steam gaming service has over 1,500 games available on Linux, compared to 2,323 games for Mac and 6,500 Windows games.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Emulation and API-translation projects like Wine and CrossOver make it possible to run non-Linux-based software on Linux systems, either by emulating a proprietary operating system or by translating proprietary API calls (e.g., calls to Microsoft's Win32 or DirectX APIs) into native Linux API calls.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] A virtual machine can also be used to run a proprietary OS (like Microsoft Windows) on top of Linux.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Pre-built computers are usually sold with an operating system other than Linux already installed by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] This limits Linux's market share: consumers are unaware that an alternative exists, they must make a conscious effort to use a different operating system, and they must either perform the actual installation themselves, or depend on support from a friend, relative, or computer professional.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] However, it is possible to buy hardware with Linux already installed.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Lenovo, Hewlett-Packard, Dell, Affordy, Purism, Pine64 and System76 all sell general-purpose Linux laptops.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Custom-order PC manufacturers will also build Linux systems, but possibly with the Windows key on the keyboard.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Fixstars Solutions (formerly Terra Soft) sold Macintosh computers and PlayStation 3 consoles with Yellow Dog Linux installed.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] It is more common to find embedded devices sold with Linux as the default manufacturer-supported OS, including the Linksys NSLU2 NAS device, TiVo's line of personal video recorders, and Linux-based cellphones (including Android smartphones), PDAs, and portable music players.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] The current Microsoft Windows license lets the manufacturer determine the refund policy.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] With prior versions of Windows, it was possible to obtain a refund if the manufacturer failed to provide the refund by litigation in the small claims courts.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] On February 15, 1999, a group of Linux users in Orange County, California held a "Windows Refund Day" protest in an attempt to pressure Microsoft into issuing them refunds.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] There are no official figures on the popularity, adoption, downloads or installed base of Linux distributions.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] There are also no official figures for the total number of Linux systems, partly due to the difficulty of quantifying the number of PCs running Linux (see Desktop Linux adoption), since many users download Linux distributions.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Hence, the sales figures for Linux systems and commercial Linux distributions indicate a much lower number of Linux systems and level of Linux adoption than is the case; this is mainly due to Linux being free and open-source software that can be downloaded free of charge.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] A Linux Counter Project had kept track of a running guesstimate of the number of Linux systems, but did not distinguish between rolling release and standard release distributions.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] It ceased operation in August 2018, though a few related blog posts were created through October 2018.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Desktop usage statistical reports for particular Linux distributions have been collected and published since July 2014 by the Linux Hardware Project.
[src:opensuse/linux-distribution] Statcounter, a web traffic analysis company, within the *operating system market share*, showed that the Linux operating systems had, according to them, 3.9% of the worldwide market share in July 2025.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The openSUSE project is sponsored by SUSE of Germany; the company released the first version as **SUSE Linux** in 1994.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Its development was opened up to the community in 2005, which marked the creation of openSUSE.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The focus of the developers is on creating a stable and user-friendly RPM-based operating system with a large target group for workstations and servers.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Additionally, the project creates a variety of related tools, such as Agama, Myrlyn, YaST, Open Build Service, openQA, Snapper, Portus, KIWI, and OSEM.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] In the past, the SUSE Linux company has focused on releasing the **SUSE Linux Personal** and **SUSE Linux Professional** box sets which included extensive printed documentation that was available for sale in retail stores.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The company's ability to sell an open-source product was largely due to the closed-source development process used.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Although SUSE Linux had always been a free software product licensed with the GNU General Public License (GNU GPL), it was only freely possible to retrieve the source code of the next release 2 months after it was ready for purchase.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] SUSE Linux' strategy was to create a technically superior Linux distribution with a large number of employed engineers, that would make users willing to pay for their distribution in retail stores.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] SUSE Linux is of German origin, its name being an acronym of "Software und System-Entwicklung" (software and systems development), and it was mainly developed in Europe.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The first version appeared in early 1994, making SUSE one of the oldest existing commercial distributions.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It is known for its YaST configuration tool.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Since the acquisition by Novell in 2004 and with the advent of openSUSE, this has been reversed: starting with version 9.2, an unsupported one-DVD ISO image of SUSE Professional was made available for download.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The FTP server continues to operate and has the advantage of "streamlined" installs, allowing the user to download only the packages the user feels they need.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The initial stable release from the openSUSE Project, SUSE Linux 10.0, was available for download just before the retail release of SUSE Linux 10.0.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] In addition, Novell discontinued the Personal version, renaming the Professional version to simply "SUSE Linux," and repricing "SUSE Linux" to about the same as the old Personal version.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] In 2006, with version 10.2, the SUSE Linux distribution was officially renamed to openSUSE, as it is pronounced similarly to "open source".
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Until version 13.2, stable fixed releases with separate maintenance streams from SLE were the project's main offering.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Since late 2015, openSUSE has been split into two main offerings, Leap, the more conservative fixed release Leap distribution based on SLE, and Tumbleweed, the rolling release distribution focused on integrating the latest stable packages from upstream projects.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] On 27 April 2011, Attachmate completed its acquisition of Novell.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Attachmate split Novell into two autonomous business units, Novell and SUSE.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Attachmate made no changes to the relationship between SUSE (formerly Novell) and the openSUSE project.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] After the 2014 merger of the Attachmate Group with Micro Focus, SUSE reaffirmed its commitment to openSUSE.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] EQT AB announced their intent to acquire SUSE on 2 July 2018.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] There were no expected changes in the relationship between SUSE and openSUSE.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This acquisition was the third acquisition of SUSE Linux since the founding of the openSUSE Project and closed on 15 March 2019.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The openSUSE Project is a community project to create, promote, improve, and document the openSUSE Linux distribution.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The openSUSE Project community, sponsored by SUSE and others, develops and maintains various distributions based on Linux.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Beyond the distributions and tools, the openSUSE Project provides a web portal for community involvement.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The community develops openSUSE collaboratively with its corporate sponsors through the Open Build Service, openQA, writing documentation, designing artwork, fostering discussions on open mailing lists and in Internet Relay Chat channels, and improving the openSUSE site through its wiki interface.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The openSUSE Project develops free software and tools and has two main Linux distributions named openSUSE Leap and openSUSE Tumbleweed.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The project has several distributions for specific purposes like MicroOS, which is an immutable operating system that hosts container workloads, and the Kubernetes certified distribution Kubic, which is a multi-purpose standalone and Kubernetes container operating system based on openSUSE MicroOS.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The project is sponsored by a number of companies and individuals, most notably SUSE, AMD, B1 Systems, Heinlein Support, and TUXEDO Computers.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The first indication that there should be a community-based Linux distribution called OpenSuSE goes back to a mail of 3 August 2005, in which at the same time the launch of the website opensuse.org was announced.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This page was available a few days later.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] One day later the launch of the community project was officially announced.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] According to its own understanding, openSUSE is a community that propagates the use of Linux and free software wherever possible.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Besides a Linux-based distribution, it develops tools like the Open Build Service and YaST.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The openSUSE Project develops the openSUSE Linux distribution as well as a large number of tools around building Linux distributions like the Open Build Service, KIWI, YaST, openQA, Snapper, Portus, and more.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The project annually hosts free software events.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The community's conference is held at a location in Europe and a summit is held at a location in Asia.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The project is controlled by its community and relies on the contributions of individuals, working as testers, writers, translators, usability experts, artists, and developers.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The project embraces a wide variety of technology, people with different levels of expertise, speaking different languages, and having different cultural backgrounds.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] There is an openSUSE Board which is responsible to lead the overall project.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The openSUSE Board provides guidance and supports existing governance structures but does not direct or control development, since community mechanisms exist to accomplish the goals of the project.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The board documents decisions and policies.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The project is self-organized without a legal structure, although the establishment of a foundation has been under consideration for some time.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] SUSE as the main sponsor exerts some influence, but the project is legally independent of SUSE. openSUSE is a "do-ocracy" in which those who do the work also decide what happens.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This is primarily the case with desktop and application development, as the sources of the base packages have been coming from SLE since the switch to the Leap development model.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] To further unify the base, the 'Closing-the-Leap-Gap' project has been started, where openSUSE Leap 15.3 will be completely based on SLE's binary packages.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] In the old development model, with each new openSUSE release (13.0, 13.1, ...), a new rolling release is set-up, which always receives new packages.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] When the new release is to occur, Tumbleweed is reset to that release, and most packages are newer than the ones in the release.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] With the switch to Leap, the development model was changed greatly: according to the *Factory First* policy, all software packages must be sent to Factory before they can be included in a distribution.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Out of Factory, a daily snapshot is taken and tested in openQA.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] A successful test is released as the next Tumbleweed snapshot.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Unlike other rolling release distributions, Tumbleweed is a *tested rolling release*, which increases stability dramatically.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Technically, Tumbleweed is the basis for MicroOS and Kubic.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Leap is a classic stable distribution approach: one release yearly, and in between, security updates and bug fixes.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This makes Leap attractive for use in servers, and desktop computers, since it needs little maintenance effort.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] For the version released in the fall of 2015, the development team settled on the name *openSUSE Leap* with the deviating version number 42.1.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] As in the openSUSE version 4.2 from May 1996, which was named S.u.S.E.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Linux at the time, the number 42 refers to the question about "life, the universe and everything" in the Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy book series.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] After that, the basis packages are received from the SUSE Linux Enterprise, while applications and desktops come from Tumbleweed.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] At the openSUSE conference held in Nuremberg in 2016, statistics were announced that since the conceptual reorientation with openSUSE Leap 42.1, increasing user numbers had been recorded.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] According to this, the number of downloads is 400,000 DVD-images per month with an increasing tendency.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Each month, 1,600 installations would be added, and 500,000 packages would be installed.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The number of *Tumbleweed* users is 60,000, half of whom frequently perform updates.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Thus, the number of *Tumbleweed* installations had doubled in the last year.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Other findings from the statistics are that most installations are done via DVD images.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The geographical distribution of users has hardly changed according to these figures.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] One-third of users are in Germany, 12% are in the US, 5% in Russia, and 3% in Brazil.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] For the openSUSE Leap 15.3 release, the software repository for openSUSE Leap and SUSE Linux Enterprise (SLE) was merged and now contains the same source code and binary packages.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] SLE 15 will be supported until 31 July 2028.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] MicroOS is an immutable, minimalist, self-maintained, and transactional system, which is mostly, but not exclusively, intended for use in edge computing or as container runtime.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The system is self-contained and transactional; it updates itself in an all-or-nothing approach (transactional) and rolls back to its prior state in case something goes wrong.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It runs from a read-only file system, preventing accidental changes and malware attacks.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The transactional update does not affect the running system.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] All software available for Tumbleweed is also available for MicroOS.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] MicroOS Desktop was the focus for the 2021 Hackweek Archived 17 August 2021 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] On 31 May 2023, openSUSE announced name changes: the GNOME version of MicroOS is now called Aeon, and the Plasma version is called Kalpa.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The Factory project is the rolling development code base for openSUSE Tumbleweed, Factory is mainly used as an internal term for openSUSE's distribution developers, and the target project for all contributions to openSUSE's main code base.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] There is a constant flow of packages going into the Factory.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] There is no freeze; therefore, the Factory repository is not guaranteed to be fully stable and is not intended to be used by humans.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The core system packages receive automated testing via openQA.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] When automated testing is completed and the repository is in a consistent state, the repository is synced to the download mirrors and published as openSUSE Tumbleweed, That usually happens several times a week.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE currently (2024) supports installation via ISO and/or over a network from repositories for a wide range of hardware and virtualization platforms.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This includes AArch64 (custom version for Raspberry Pi is available), Arm8, POWER8 (ppc64le), IBM zSystems (s390x), the ubiquitous Intel 64 (x86-64), i586, and i686.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Arm8 (including earlier Raspberry Pi models), i586, and i686 are available in 32-bit version only.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Specialized releases for use in containers and virtualized environments are available for onie, Microsoft Hyper-V, kvm, xen, Digital Ocean Cloud, Container Host with VMware, Vagrant, and VirtualBox.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It can also be installed in conventional virtualization environments with a range of architectures e.g. using VirtualBox, VMWare, or Hyper-V.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE Leap currently supports: aarch64, ppc64le, s390x, x86_64.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Agama is the system installer for openSUSE Leap since openSUSE Leap 16, replacing the YaST Installer.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Agama handles hard disk partitioning and system setup.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Cockpit is the configuration tool for openSUSE Leap since openSUSE Leap 16, replacing the YaST Control Center.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Cockpit handles online updates, network and firewall configuration, SELinux configuration, and user administration.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Myrlyn is the software manager for openSUSE Leap since openSUSE Leap 16, replacing the YaST Software.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Myrlyn handles RPM package management and online updates.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] SUSE includes an installation and administration program called YaST ("Yet another Setup Tool") which handles hard disk partitioning, system setup, RPM package management, online updates, network, and firewall configuration, user administration and more in an integrated interface.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] By 2010, many more YaST modules were added, including one for Bluetooth support.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It also controls all software applications.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] SaX2 was once integrated into YaST to change monitor settings, however, with openSUSE 11.3 SaX2 has been removed.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The GTK user interface was removed starting with Leap 42.1, however, the ncurses and Qt interfaces remain.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] YaST was deprecated starting with Leap 16 with the Qt interface removed, however, the ncurses interface is still available to download and use.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] AutoYaST is part of YaST2 and is used for automatic installation.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The configuration is stored in an XML file and the installation happens without user interaction.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] WebYaST is a web interface version of YaST.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It can configure settings and updates of the openSUSE machine it is running on.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It can also shut down and check the status of the host.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] ZYpp (or libzypp) is a Linux software management engine.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] ZYpp is the backend for zypper, the default command line package management tool for openSUSE.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The Open Build Service provides software developers with a tool to compile, release and publish their software for many distributions, including Mandriva, Ubuntu, Fedora and Debian.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It typically simplifies the packaging process, so developers can more easily package a single program for many distributions, and many openSUSE releases, making more packages available to users regardless of what distribution version they use.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] By default, openSUSE uses Delta RPMs when updating an installation.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] A Delta RPM contains the difference between an old and a new version of a package.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This means that only the changes between the installed package and the new one, are downloaded.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This reduces bandwidth consumption and update time, which is especially important on slow Internet connections.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] SUSE was a leading contributor to the KDE project for many years.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] SUSE's contributions in this area have been very wide-ranging, and affecting many parts of KDE such as kdelibs and KDEBase, Kontact, and kdenetwork.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Other notable projects include: *KNetworkManager* – a front-end to NetworkManager and *Kickoff* – a new K menu for KDE Plasma Desktop.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] From openSUSE Leap 42.1 to 15.0, the default Plasma 5 desktop for openSUSE used the traditional cascading *Application Menu* in place of the upstream default *Kickoff*-like *Application Launcher* menu.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The openSUSE Leap KDE experience is built on long-term support versions of KDE Plasma, starting with openSUSE Leap 42.2.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] With openSUSE Leap 15.1, the Plasma 5 desktop now again defaults to the *Kickoff*-style application menu.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The Ximian group became part of Novell, and in turn made and continued several contributions to GNOME with applications such as F-Spot, Evolution and Banshee.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The GNOME desktop used the *slab* instead of the classic double-panelled GNOME menu bars from openSUSE 10.2 to openSUSE 11.4.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] In openSUSE 12.1 *slab* was replaced with the upstream GNOME Shell and GNOME Fallback designs.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Starting with openSUSE Leap 15.0, GNOME on Wayland is offered as the default GNOME session.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] GNOME Classic, GNOME on Xorg, and "GNOME SLE" are offered as alternative sessions to the more upstream Wayland-based session.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The initial stable release from the openSUSE Project was SUSE Linux 10.0, released on 6 October 2005.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This was released as a freely downloadable ISO image and as a boxed retail package, with certain bundled software only included in the retail package.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] On 11 May 2006, the openSUSE Project released SUSE Linux 10.1, with the mailing list announcement identifying Xgl, NetworkManager, AppArmor and Xen as prominent features.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] For their third release, the openSUSE Project renamed their distribution, releasing openSUSE 10.2 on 7 December 2006.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This release also featured version 2.0 of Mozilla Firefox.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The fourth release, openSUSE 10.3, was made available as a stable version on 4 October 2007.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] An overhaul of the software package management system (including support for 1-Click-Install), legal MP3 support from Fluendo and improved boot-time are some of the areas focused on for this release.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE 11.0 was released on 19 June 2008.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It includes the latest version of GNOME and two versions of KDE (the older, stable 3.5.9 and the newer 4.0.4).
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It comes in three freely downloadable versions: a complete installation DVD (including GNOME, KDE 3, and KDE SC 4), and two Live CDs (GNOME, and KDE SC 4 respectively).
[src:opensuse/opensuse] A KDE 3 Live CD was not produced due to limited resources.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Package management and installation were made significantly faster with ZYpp.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE 11.1 was released on 18 December 2008.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE 11.2 was released on 12 November 2009.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE 11.3 was released on 15 July 2010.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It includes Plasma 4.4.4, GNOME 2.30.1, Mozilla Firefox 3.6.6, OpenOffice.org 3.2.1, SpiderOak support, support for the Btrfs filesystem and support for LXDE.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It also updates the Linux kernel to version 2.6.34.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE 11.4 was finished on 3 March 2011, and released on 10 March 2011.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It includes Plasma 4.6.0, GNOME 2.32.1, Mozilla Firefox 4.0 beta 12, and switched from OpenOffice.org to LibreOffice 3.3.1.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It updates the Linux kernel to version 2.6.37.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE 12.1 was released on 16 November 2011.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This includes Plasma 4.7 and GNOME 3.2 and Firefox 7.0.1.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The Linux kernel was updated to 3.1.0 It also introduced an advanced disk snapshot tool, called Snapper, for managing Btrfs snapshots. openSUSE 12.1 was also the first release of openSUSE to use systemd by default rather than the traditional System V init.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Users can still select to boot to System V init at startup time.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE 12.2 was to be released on 11 July 2012, but was postponed due to persistent stability issues.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The final release candidate was eventually announced on 2 August 2012, and the final release date was 5 September 2012.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] 12.2 includes the desktop environments Plasma 4.8, GNOME 3.4, Firefox 14.0.1, and Xfce 4.10 and now uses Plymouth and GRUB 2 by default.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE 12.3 was released on schedule on 13 March 2013.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This includes Plasma 4.10, GNOME 3.6, Firefox 19.0, LibreOffice 3.6, and the removal of SuSEconfig.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Also, the Live CD images were replaced with Live USB images, and an Xfce rescue image.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE 13.1 was released on 19 November 2013, and includes updates to Plasma 4.11, GNOME 3.10, Firefox 25.0, and LibreOffice 4.1.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Some other changes include a YaST port to Ruby, the LightDM KDE greeter, and experimental Wayland support in the GNOME Shell and KDE Plasma Desktop. openSUSE 13.1 is an Evergreen supported release, meaning it will receive community patches for 18 months after SUSE support ends.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE 13.2 was released on 4 November 2014, and includes updates to Plasma 4.11, KDE Applications 4.14, GNOME 3.14.1, Firefox 33.0 and LibreOffice 4.3.2.2.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The openSUSE team decided that the next version would be based on SUSE Linux Enterprise Server (SLES).
[src:opensuse/opensuse] They named it "Leap 42" (42 being the answer to life, the universe and everything); this was a temporary anomaly in the version number sequence, as the following release series was numbered 15.X.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Leap 42.2 features KDE Plasma 5.8 LTS as its default desktop environment.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE Leap 15 is based on SUSE Linux Enterprise (SLE).
[src:opensuse/opensuse] The name "Leap 15" is meant to match the SUSE Linux Enterprise version it is based on.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Leap 15 (just like SUSE Linux Enterprise 15) uses Linux kernel 4.12 LTS, and the default desktop is KDE Plasma 5.12 LTS.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It also allows users to switch to its enterprise variant - SUSE Linux Enterprise 15.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Leap 15.5 (released on 7 June 2023) uses Linux kernel 5.14.21, KDE Plasma 5.27 and comes with a new support of Python 3.11.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It is expected to be the penultimate release of Leap 15, with version 15.6 released on 12 June 2024.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] openSUSE Leap 16 was released on 1 October 2025, this version is based on SUSE Linux Enterprise 16.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] This version features SELinux as default Linux Security Module replacing AppArmor (AppArmor is still available if users want to use it).
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Agama is used as system installer replacing YaST.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] It also features an improved version of Zypper with support for parallel downloads.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Starting with version **Leap** (after version 13.2), each major release (e.g.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] 15.0) is expected to be supported for at least 36 months, until the next major version is available (e.g.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] 16.0), aligned with SUSE Linux Enterprise Releases.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] 15.5, 15.6 etc.) is expected to be released annually, aligned with SUSE Linux Enterprise Service Packs, and users are expected to upgrade to the latest minor release within 6 months of its availability, leading to an expected support lifecycle of 18 months.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] From 2009 to 2014, the openSUSE project aimed to release a new version every eight months.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Prior to the Leap series, versions 11.2-13.2 were provided with critical updates for two releases plus two months, which resulted in an expected support lifetime of 18 months.
[src:opensuse/opensuse] Jesse Smith from DistroWatch Weekly reviewed openSUSE Leap 15.0, lauding the "work that has gone into the system installer", simplify for new users, but criticized the lack of media support, and performance issues, like a slow startup or slow shutdown.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Although it was created for use in Red Hat Linux, RPM is now used in many Linux distributions such as PCLinuxOS, Fedora Linux, AlmaLinux, CentOS, openSUSE, OpenMandriva and Oracle Linux.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] It has also been ported to some other operating systems, such as Novell NetWare (as of version 6.5 SP3), IBM's AIX (as of version 4), IBM i, and ArcaOS.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] An RPM package can contain an arbitrary set of files.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Most RPM files are "binary RPMs" (or BRPMs) containing the compiled version of some software.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] There are also "source RPMs" (or SRPMs) containing the source code used to build a binary package.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] These have an appropriate tag in the file header that distinguishes them from normal (B)RPMs, causing them to be extracted to /usr/src on installation.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] SRPMs customarily carry the file extension ".src.rpm" (.spm on file systems limited to 3 extension characters, e.g. old DOS FAT).
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] RPM was originally written in 1997 by Erik Troan and Marc Ewing, based on `pms`, `rpp`, and `pm` experiences.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] `pm` was written by Rik Faith and Doug Hoffman in May 1995 for Red Hat Software, its design and implementations were influenced greatly by `pms`, a package management system by Faith and Kevin Martin in the fall of 1993 for the Bogus Linux Distribution.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] `pm` preserves the "Pristine Sources + patches" paradigm of `pms`, while adding features and eliminating arbitrary limitations present in the implementation.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] `pm` provides greatly enhanced database support for tracking and verifying installed packages.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Packages may come from within a particular distribution (for example Red Hat Enterprise Linux) or be built for it by other parties (for example RPM Fusion for Fedora Linux).
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Circular dependencies among mutually dependent RPMs (so-called "dependency hell") can be problematic; in such cases a single installation command needs to specify all the relevant packages.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] RPMs are often collected centrally in one or more repositories on the internet.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] A site often has its own RPM repositories which may either act as local mirrors of such internet repositories or be locally maintained collections of useful RPMs.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Several front-ends to RPM ease the process of obtaining and installing RPMs from repositories and help in resolving their dependencies.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Working behind the scenes of the package manager is the RPM database, stored in `/var/lib/rpm`.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] It consists of a single database (`Packages`) containing all of the meta information of the installed RPMs.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Multiple databases are created for indexing purposes, replicating data to speed up queries.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] The database is used to keep track of all files that are changed and created when a user (using RPM) installs a package, thus enabling the user (via RPM) to reverse the changes and remove the package later.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] If the database gets corrupted (which is possible if the RPM client is killed), the index databases can be recreated with the `rpm --rebuilddb` command.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Whilst the RPM format is the same across different Linux distributions, the detailed conventions and guidelines may vary across them.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] RPMs with the `noarch.rpm` extension do not depend on a particular CPU architecture.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] For example, these RPMs may contain graphics and text for other programs to use.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] They may also contain shell scripts or programs written in other interpreted programming languages such as Python.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] The package label fields do not need to match the filename.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Libraries are distributed in two separate packages for each version.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] One contains the precompiled code for use at run-time, while the second one contains the related development files such as headers, etc.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Those packages have "-devel" appended to their name field.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] The system administrator should ensure that the versions of the binary and development packages match.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] The "Recipe" for creating an RPM package is a spec file.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Spec files end in the ".spec" suffix and contain the package name, version, RPM revision number, steps to build, install, and clean a package, and a changelog.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Multiple packages can be built from a single RPM spec file, if desired.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] RPM packages are created from RPM spec files using the rpmbuild tool.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Spec files are usually distributed within SRPM files, which contain the spec file packaged along with the source code.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] A typical RPM is pre-compiled software ready for direct installation.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] The corresponding source code can also be distributed.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] This is done in an SRPM, which also includes the "SPEC" file describing the software and how it is built.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] The SRPM also allows the user to compile, and perhaps modify, the code itself.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] A software package could contain only platform independent scripts.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] In such a case, the developer could provide only an SRPM, which is still an installable RPM.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] It contains "SPEC" file and optionally patches, but does not include sources (usually because of license).
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] As of June 2010, there are two versions of RPM in development: one led by the Fedora Project and Red Hat, and the other by a separate group led by a previous maintainer of RPM, a former employee of Red Hat.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] The *rpm.org* community's first major code revision was in July 2007; version 4.8 was released in January 2010, version 4.9 in March 2011, 4.10 in May 2012, 4.11 in January 2013, 4.12 in September 2014 and 4.13 in July 2015.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] This version is used by distributions such as Fedora Linux, Red Hat Enterprise Linux and derivatives, openSUSE, SUSE Linux Enterprise, Unity Linux, Mageia, OpenEmbedded, Tizen and OpenMandriva Lx (formerly Mandriva).
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] Jeff Johnson, the RPM maintainer since 1999, continued development efforts together with participants from several other distributions.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] This version was used by distributions such as Wind River Linux (until Wind River Linux 10), Rosa Linux, and OpenMandriva Lx (former Mandriva Linux which switched to rpm5 in 2011) and also by the OpenPKG project which provides packages for other common UNIX-platforms.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] OpenMandriva Lx has switched back to rpm.org for 4.0 release.
[src:opensuse/rpm-package-manager] OpenEmbedded, the last major user of RPM5, switched back to rpm.org due to issues in RPM5.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Its major versions are released at an interval of three–four years, while minor versions (called "Service Packs" until SLE 15 or "Minor Release" starting with SLE 16) are released about every 12 months.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SUSE Linux Enterprise products receive more intense testing than the upstream openSUSE community product, with the intention that only mature, stable versions of the included components will make it through to the released enterprise product.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] It is developed from a common code base with other SUSE Linux Enterprise products.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] IBM's Watson was built on IBM's POWER7 systems using SLES.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Hewlett Packard Enterprise's Frontier, world's first and fastest exascale supercomputer runs on SUSE's SLES 15 (HPE Cray OS).
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLES was developed based on SUSE Linux by a small team led by Marcus Kraft and Bernhard Kaindl as principal developer who were supported by Joachim "Jos" Schröder.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] It was first released on 31 October 2000 as a version for IBM S/390 mainframe machines.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] In December 2000, the first enterprise client (Telia) was made public.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] In April 2001, the first SLES for x86 was released.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] From a business perspective, SLES is not only a technical offering, but also has entangled a commercial offering (services and support).
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] The initial business model was inspired by recurrent charges established in the mainframe world at this time, and innovated by Jürgen Geck and Malcom Yates.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Based on customer needs and feedback as well as other evolving Linux based offerings the business model has been reworked by different people in the subsequent years until today.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] The **SLES 13** and **SLES 14** version numbers were skipped due to superstitions associated with those numbers in certain cultures.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLED since version 12 has included a modified version of the GNOME Classic Shell to include a layout with one panel on the bottom of the screen, traditional application menus, and desktop icons for traditional desktop users.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] It also includes LibreOffice, Mozilla Firefox, and Evolution along with many standard GNOME utilities, such as GNOME Documents and GNOME Files.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] As well, the YaST Control Center allows end users to make advanced changes to the system from the command line.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] HP offers business notebooks with SLED 11 preinstalled, under both its own brand and the Compaq brand.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Micro-Star International offered MSI Wind Netbooks with SLED 10 preinstalled.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Sun Microsystems previously licensed SLED as the basis of the Linux version of Java Desktop System.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] In March 2018, SUSE Product Manager Jay Kruemcke wrote in SUSE blog that SUSE Linux Enterprise developers have ported it to Raspberry Pi.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SUSE Linux Enterprise Desktop has been developed while SUSE was under the ownership of several different parent companies.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SUSE was owned by and conducted business as Novell from SLED's first release as Novell Linux Desktop in 2004 until 2011 when The Attachmate Group purchased Novell and created SUSE as an autonomous subsidiary.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Micro Focus in turn purchased The Attachmate Group in 2014 and made SUSE an autonomous business unit, before selling it to EQT AB in 2019.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] EQT AB is a private equity group that develops new companies before divesting them as independent companies.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Novell Linux Desktop (NLD) 9 was originally released on 8 November 2004, less than a year after Novell's acquisition of SUSE.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] There were a number of Service Packs (SP's) released for NLD 9.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SP1 was released on 11 February 2005 and contained many updates.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] After that, SP2 was released on 9 August 2005, containing all the released updates and bugfixes since August 2004.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] NLD 9 was based on SUSE Linux 9.1 and offered a more conservative offering of desktop applications for businesses.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Its desktop included common end user applications like Mozilla Firefox, OpenOffice.org.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] NLD also included software developed by Novell and its 2003 acquisition Ximian, such as the Red Carpet software management tool from Ximian and Novell's system management tool ZenWorks.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] With SLED 10, Novell increased the focus on features for a broader range of corporate users by focusing on meeting the needs for basic office workers, positioning SLED as a competitor to Microsoft Windows.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Basic office workers were defined in this context as users who need basic desktop functionality, including an office suite, a collaboration client, a web browser, and instant messaging.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Novell attempts to meet these needs by concentrating on making these components very compatible with existing enterprise infrastructure, such as Microsoft Office data files, Microsoft Active Directory, and Microsoft Exchange Server or Novell GroupWise collaboration systems.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] It also included the Beagle desktop search tool, similar to Spotlight in Mac OS X v10.4.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] The Xgl+Compiz support enables a variety of advanced graphical effects in the user interface, such as "application tiling" (similar to Exposé).
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Other features include making it easier for Linux beginners to connect digital cameras to the computer and play audio files such as MP3s using Helix Banshee.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] The version of GNOME included this release was highly customized, and debuted the *slab* application menu on a one panel layout.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLED 10 was originally released on 17 June 2006.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] The last service pack for SLED 10 was Service Pack 4, released on 15 April 2011.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLED 11, based on openSUSE 11.1, was released on 24 March 2009.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] It included an upgrade to GNOME and was the first release to ship KDE 4, with version 4.1.3.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Several improvements were made to improve Microsoft Active Directory and Microsoft Exchange Server integration, and the Novell OpenOffice.org version was upgraded to version 3.0.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLED continued to include some proprietary components such as Adobe Flash, as well as open-source implementations of closed sourced plugins and runtimes such as Moonlight and Mono.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Four service packs were released for SLED 11, with Service Pack 2 notably bringing Btrfs commercial support to the enterprise Linux market and including the snapper tool to manage Btrfs snapshots.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] The most current service pack, SP 4, was released on 17 July 2015.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] On 28 October 2014, SUSE (now an independent business unit) released SLED 12 built on openSUSE 13.1.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLED 12 introduced several new technological upgrades, including systemd, GNOME 3, GRUB 2, plymouth, and the in-house built wicked wireless network manager.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLED 12 also included further stability and integration with BtrFS.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] With the transition to GNOME 3, the GNOME Classic Shell, the vanilla GNOME Shell, and a SLE Classic Shell with a design that more closely mimics the slab layout were included.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] KDE, the default desktop environment in openSUSE, and support for 32-bit x86 processors were dropped from the enterprise distribution.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLE 12 Service Pack 1 was the first to be the basis for openSUSE's more conservative Leap series, with openSUSE Leap 42.1 sharing its codebase with SLE 12 SP1.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Leap 42.2 and 42.3 were built from the same codebase as SLE 12 SP2 and SLE SP3 respectively.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLED 12's underlying base, SUSE Linux Enterprise Server 12, was the first version of SLE to be offered on the Microsoft Store to be run on the Windows Subsystem for Linux.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLE skipped over versions 13 and 14, realigning the versions of openSUSE Leap and SLE at version 15.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLE 15 was released on 25 June 2018 with the same codebase as openSUSE Leap 15.0.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLED 15 included major upgrades to GNOME 3.26, LibreOffice 6.0, GCC 7 and LTS kernel version 4.12.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Version 15 also made the Wayland implementation of GNOME the default.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLES and SLED can now also be installed from the same media.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLED 15 offers the same GNOME Desktop options as SLED 12.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLE 15 SP1 shares a common codebase with openSUSE Leap 15.1.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLE 15 SP 1 includes improvements to the ability to migrate from openSUSE Leap to SLE, increased 64-bit Arm System on a Chip (SoC) supported processor options, transactional updates, and various other features.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLE 15 SP3 features a unified repository with same source code and binary packages with openSUSE Leap 15.3.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Novell's effort on SUSE Linux Enterprise Desktop 10 was led by Nat Friedman, one of the two founders of Ximian.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Nat was aided by a host of former Ximian and SUSE developers, with product manager Guy Lunardi and engineering manager Kelli Frame.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Through SUSE Studio Express, users can create custom appliances based on SUSE Linux Distributions including SLED.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Options for SLE allow for the creation of derivative distributions as custom Kiwi and docker containers with customized package choices and configuration parameters.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] There are two suites of administrative tools used on SUSE Linux Enterprise, one is the suite introduced with SLE 16.0 consisting of Agama (system installer), Cockpit (configuration tool), and Mylryn (package management) and another one is YaST used with SLE 15 and older versions of SLE.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Agama is the system installer for SUSE Linux Enterprise since SLE 16.0, replacing the YaST Installer.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Cockpit is the configuration tool for SUSE Linux Enterprise since SLE 16.0, replacing the YaST Control Center.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Myrlyn is the software manager for SUSE Linux Enterprise since SLE 16.0, replacing the YaST Software.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] YaST is the configuration tool in the SUSE Linux distributions, up to and including SLE 15.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] YaST is an installation and administration program which can handle hard disk partitioning, system setup, RPM package management, online updates, network and firewall configuration, user administration and more in an integrated interface consisting of various modules for each administrative task.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SUSE Package Hub gives SLE users the option to install packages that are not an official part of the SUSE Linux Enterprise distribution or are more up to date than those included with the latest version of SLE.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SUSE Package Hub is unofficial, and the software installed from its repositories does not receive commercial support from SUSE.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Currently about 9,000 packages are available from SUSE Package Hub for SLE 12 and 15 with packages available for AArch64, ppc64le, s390x, and x86-64.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Legacy versions of SUSE Linux Enterprise (SLES 9 and 10) had a ten year product lifecycle.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] Newer versions have a thirteen year product lifecycle (SLES 11, 12, and 15).
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] The current support model consists of 10 years of general support from time of First Customer Shipment (FCS), followed by 3 years of Long Term Service Pack Support (LTSS), and 3 years more of LTSS Core.
[src:opensuse/suse-linux-enterprise] SLES 16 changed Service Pack to Minor Release and Long Term Service Pack Support to Long Term Support (LTS).
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST is featured in the openSUSE Linux distribution, as well as in SUSE's derived commercial distributions including SUSE Linux Enterprise.
[src:opensuse/yast] It is also part of the defunct United Linux.
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST features tools that can configure many aspects of the system.
[src:opensuse/yast] The first SuSE distribution that included YaST was released in May 1996.
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST was re-written in 1999 and included first in SuSE Linux 6.3 as only an installer.
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST2 was added to the desktop in SuSE Linux 6.4 and co-existed with YaST1 until YaST1's removal in SuSE Linux 8.0.
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST was deprecated starting with openSUSE Leap 16 with the Qt interface removed, however, the ncurses interface is still available to download and use.
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST is free and open-source software that SUSE has made available under the GNU General Public License (GPL) in 2004.
[src:opensuse/yast] It is a tool for administering and maintaining a SUSE Linux installation.
[src:opensuse/yast] It allows system administrators to install software, configure hardware, set up networks and servers, and more.
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST also features two front ends: a graphical user interface (GUI) and a text-based user interface (TUI) (with ncurses).
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST offers package managing functions through the ZYpp project.
[src:opensuse/yast] The first ZYpp enabled package management YaST applications had performance problems and long start up times, but was improved in the 10.2 and 10.3 releases.
[src:opensuse/yast] Starting with openSUSE 11.0 alpha 3, ZYpp was integrated with the SAT solver project, making YaST and Zypper faster than other RPM Package Manager based systems.
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST used to include SaX and SaX2, the Suse Advanced X configuration.
[src:opensuse/yast] SaX was re-written as SaX2 in SuSE Linux 6.4.
[src:opensuse/yast] SaX1 was removed in SuSE Linux 8.1 and SaX2 was removed from the YaST Control Center in openSUSE 11.2.
[src:opensuse/yast] SaX2 was removed completely in openSUSE 11.3.
[src:opensuse/yast] The GTK interface was removed in openSUSE Leap 42.1.
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST often receives updates and improvements in Tumbleweed and between versions of Leap. openSUSE Leap 15.1, for example, saw improvements to the YaST interface for managing firewalls including the addition of an interface in the command line version of YaST.
[src:opensuse/yast] In this same release of openSUSE Leap, YaST now has an updated logo and improved partition management module.
[src:opensuse/yast] YaST formerly used a bespoke scripting language named YCP; in OpenSUSE 13.1, YaST was rewritten in Ruby.
[src:opensuse/yast] On openSUSE Leap 16 and SUSE Linux Enterprise Server 16, YaST was deprecated.
[src:opensuse/yast] The web-based Cockpit project was adopted to supplant the YaST Control Center, a web-based installer named Agama replaced the YaST installer, and Myrlyn was introduced as a new Qt-based ZYpp front end with no dependency on YaST, replaced YaST Software.
[src:opensuse/yast] AutoYaST is a system for installing one or more openSUSE systems automatically without user intervention.
[src:opensuse/yast] AutoYaST installations are performed using a control file with installation and configuration data.
[src:opensuse/yast] The profile of each current system is stored in `/root/autoyast.xml`.
[src:opensuse/yast] WebYaST is a web interface for YaST that can be used to check the status of the current machine.
[src:opensuse/yast] It can check on the installation of packages, shutdown or reboot the system, change some system settings (such as the time), and change the status of system services or daemons.
[src:opensuse/yast] The change of license of YaST from a previous rather restrictive license to the GPL in 2004 made it possible to port YaST to other Linux distributions.
[src:opensuse/yast] As a consequence of this, the project *YaST4Debian* was launched, which worked on a port of YaST to Debian.
[src:opensuse/yast] The project, which was in contact with the YaST team of Novell/SuSE, reached some important milestones, such as the port of the modules *yast2-ncurses* and *yast2-qt*.
[src:opensuse/yast] Currently, the project is dormant, searching for a new voluntary project maintainer.
[src:opensuse/zypp] Following its consecutive acquisitions of Ximian and SuSE GmbH in 2003, Novell decided to merge both package management systems, YaST package manager and Red Carpet, in a best of breed approach, as the two solutions so far were used at Novell.
[src:opensuse/zypp] Libzypp, the resulting library, was planned to be the software management engine of the SUSE distributions and the Linux Management component of the Novell ZENworks Management suite.
[src:opensuse/zypp] The Libzypp's solver was a port from the Red Carpet solver, which was written to update packages in installed systems.
[src:opensuse/zypp] Using it for the full installing process brought it to its limits, and adding extensions such as support for weak dependencies and patches made it fragile and unpredictable.
[src:opensuse/zypp] Although this first version of ZYpp's solver worked satisfactorily, on the company enterprise products with the coupled ZMD daemon, it led to an openSUSE 10.1 release which came out in May 2006 with a system package not working as expected.
[src:opensuse/zypp] In December 2006, the openSUSE 10.2 release corrected some defects of the prior release, using the revisited ZYpp v2.
[src:opensuse/zypp] ZMD was subsequently removed from the 10.3 release and reserved for only the company Enterprise products.
[src:opensuse/zypp] While ZYpp v3 provided openSUSE with a relatively good package manager, equivalent to other existing package managers, it suffered from some flaws in its implementation which greatly limited its speed performance.
[src:opensuse/zypp] An area where libzypp needed improvement was the speed of the dependency solver. libsolv is being written and released under the revised BSD license.
[src:opensuse/zypp] Projects like Optimal Package Install/Uninstall Manager (OPIUM) and MANCOOSI were trying to fix dependency solving issues with a SAT solver.
[src:opensuse/zypp] Traditional solvers like Advanced Packaging Tool (APT) sometimes show unacceptable deficiencies.
[src:opensuse/zypp] It was decided to integrate SAT algorithms into the ZYpp stack; the solver algorithms used were based on the popular minisat solver.
[src:opensuse/zypp] After several months of work, the benchmark results of this fourth ZYpp version integrated with the SAT solver were more than encouraging, moving YaST and Zypper ahead of other RPM-based package managers in speed and size.
[src:opensuse/zypp] Typically, YaST has served as the graphical front end for ZYpp in SUSE.
[src:opensuse/zypp] Starting in 2025 with openSUSE Leap 16.0, YaST was replaced by Myrlyn.
